/*

https://leetcode.com/problems/min-stack/description/?envType=company&envId=nvidia&favoriteSlug=nvidia-three-months

Design a stack that supports push, pop, top, and retrieving the minimum element in constant time.

Implement the MinStack class:

MinStack() initializes the stack object.
void push(int val) pushes the element val onto the stack.
void pop() removes the element on the top of the stack.
int top() gets the top element of the stack.
int getMin() retrieves the minimum element in the stack.
You must implement a solution with O(1) time complexity for each function.

 

Example 1:

Input
["MinStack","push","push","push","getMin","pop","top","getMin"]
[[],[-2],[0],[-3],[],[],[],[]]

Output
[null,null,null,null,-3,null,0,-2]

Explanation
MinStack minStack = new MinStack();
minStack.push(-2);
minStack.push(0);
minStack.push(-3);
minStack.getMin(); // return -3
minStack.pop();
minStack.top();    // return 0
minStack.getMin(); // return -2
 

Constraints:

-231 <= val <= 231 - 1
Methods pop, top and getMin operations will always be called on non-empty stacks.
At most 3 * 104 calls will be made to push, pop, top, and getMin.

*/

/*
I will use two stacks.

One stack, stk, stores all the actual values.

Another stack, minStk, stores only the values that are minimum at some point.

The idea is:

When I push a value into the main stack, I check whether it is smaller than or equal to the current minimum.
If yes, I also push it into minStk.
The top of minStk will always represent the current minimum element.
When I pop from the main stack, if the removed value is equal to the current minimum, then I also pop from minStk.

This allows getMin() to simply return:

*/

class MinStack {

    private Stack<Integer> stack;
    private Stack<Integer> minStack;

    public MinStack() {
        stack = new Stack<>();
        minStack = new Stack<>();
    }

    public void push(int val) {
        stack.push(val);

        // If minStack is empty, val is the current minimum.
        // Otherwise, compare val with current minimum.
        if (minStack.isEmpty()) {
            minStack.push(val);
        } else {
            minStack.push(Math.min(val, minStack.peek()));
        }
    }

    public void pop() {
        stack.pop();
        minStack.pop();
    }

    public int top() {
        return stack.peek();
    }

    public int getMin() {
        return minStack.peek();
    }
}
